# Project #2
## Introduction

####    The purpose of this project is to review how temperature impacts a person's stress level. Specifically, we will
#### review how overall temperature affects the number of aggravated assault arrests in the immediate region.
#### 
####    In the initial project with RStudio, we reviewed how temperature aggravated assault arrest numbers with the 
#### Maricopa County Sheriff's Office (MCSO) and we used the National Centers for Environmental Information temperature reading
#### for Maricopa County as the benchmark for our temperature. However, one identified limitation is that MCSO is not the only agency
#### that operates within Maricopa County. 
####
####    Going into the project- initially- we hypothesized that heat would have a positive correlation with aggravated assault arrests; i.e.,
#### it was expected that as heat increased the number of aggravated assaults arrests increased. However, we saw that our data indicated
#### almost no correlation between heat and aggravated assault arrests, and actually stated that as heat increased the number of aggravated
#### assault arrests decreased. This could possibly indicate that there is a threshold that, once reached, human-behavior may prefer energy
#### conservation (from the heat) and would rather seek cooler areas that engage in assaultive behavior.
####
####    For this final project, we will once again be reviewing how heat impacts the number of aggravated assault arrests. However, for this
#### data set we will be utilizing the data of the 10 most populuous States of the 50 States and we will be utilizing the aggravated assault
#### arrests for each of these mentioned States.

## The Data for Population

#### The population numbers are derived from the United States Census Bureau at `census.gov/popclock` and- in order to maximize
