## Weather Data

#### Now that we have identified the 10 most populous States in The United States of America, we will now take a look at the temperature
#### trend for these States. 
####
#### In order to obtain this data, we navigate to the National Centers for Environmental Information website for <b>Clime at a Glance
#### <b>Statewide Time Series</b> at the following URL:
#### `https://www.ncei.noaa.gov/access/monitoring/climate-at-a-glance/statewide/time-series`.
####
#### We will rotate through the State names (California, Florida, Georgia, etc) and we will select the following toggles:
#### Parameter: Maximum Temperature
#### Time Scale: 36-Month
#### Start Year: 2024
#### End Year: 2026
####
#### Then we download the file as a CSV. The reason we use 36-months is to ensure that we include the timeframes between February 2024
#### through February 2026 and we can then trim out data within Jupyter.
####
#### For the temperature parameter, the maximum temperature was selected due to the hottest part over a 24-hour period would typically
#### happen in daytime- at some time between 10am and 4pm- as noted on this Mississippi State University article titled
#### <em>Tips for Heat and Sun Safety</em> where Author Michaela Parker cautions reader to "[a]void heavy physical exertion during the 
#### hottest part of the day, from 10 a.m. until 4 p.m." (Parker, Tips for heat and Sun Safety). This would provide a more typical timeframe for human interaction
#### and a temperature that better reflects what a normal human being would experience while interacting with another human being.


weather_files = {
    'California': 'CAWeather.csv',
    'Texas': 'TXWeather.csv',
    'Florida': 'FLWeather.csv',
    'New York': 'NYWeather.csv',
    'Pennsylvania': 'PAWeather.csv',
    'Illinois': 'ILWeather.csv',
    'Ohio': 'OHWeather.csv',
    'Georgia': 'GAWeather.csv',
    'North Carolina': 'NCWeather.csv',
    'Michigan': 'MIWeather.csv'
}

weather_list = []

## We used a nifty little for loop to merge the files instead of
## doing it one by one as we did above for the assault data

for state, file in weather_files.items():
    temp = pd.read_csv(file, skiprows=2)
    
    temp['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(
        temp['Date'].astype(str),
        format='%Y%m',
        errors='coerce'
    )
    
    temp['MaxTemp'] = pd.to_numeric(temp['Value'], errors='coerce')
    temp['State'] = state
    
    temp = temp[['State', 'Date', 'MaxTemp']]
    
    weather_list.append(temp)

weather_all = pd.concat(weather_list, ignore_index=True)

weather_byDate = weather_all[
    (weather_all['Date'] >= '2024-02-01') &
    (weather_all['Date'] <= '2026-02-28')
]

weather_byDate


#### And now we will graph the Maximum Temperature Graph by State

weatherGraph = weather_byDate.pivot_table(
    index='Date',
    columns='State',
    values='MaxTemp'
)

weatherGraph.plot(figsize=(12,6))

plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Max Temperature in Fahrenheit')
plt.title('Max Temperature by State (February 2024 - February 2026)')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.legend(title='State')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

## The next step in this process is to now merge the Weather data with the Assault data.

assault_byDate = byDate.rename(columns={'Month': 'Date'})

merged = pd.merge(
    assault_byDate,
    weather_byDate,
    on=['State', 'Date'],
    how='inner'
)
weather_byDate


assault_byDate

merged 
## I printed both of the datasets separately, before the merge, in order to ensure the merge functioned properly
## Number of rows match, head and tail match, [1] extra column

correlation = merged['Assaults'].corr(merged['MaxTemp'])
print("Overall correlation:", correlation)

## Weak overall correlation, which is to be expected when you consider the graph that shows each
## States' weather data. The graph shows that each State will have it's own weather pattern/average
## so if we consider an aggragate view of assaults and weather (not considering geographic locations)
## the correlation is pretty weak.

byStateCorr = merged.groupby('State').apply(
    lambda x: x['Assaults'].corr(x['MaxTemp'])
)

print(byStateCorr)

#### Now, it appears that there isn't much correlation for most of the States, except for New York (correlation .84), North Carolina
#### (correlation .82) and Pennsylvania (correlation .80).
####
#### We will now graph the data to review it visually.

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))

for state in merged['State'].unique():
    temp = merged[merged['State'] == state]

    plt.scatter(
    temp['MaxTemp'],
    temp['Assaults'],
    label=state
    )

plt.xlabel('Max Temperature in Fahrenheit')
plt.ylabel('Aggravated Assault Arrests')
plt.title('Temperature vs Aggravated Assaults by State')
plt.legend()
