#### I reformatted this graph to make it a bit easier to digest as well

states = merged['State'].unique()

fig, axes = plt.subplots(2,5, figsize=(18,8))
axes = axes.flatten()

for i, state in enumerate(states):
    axs = axes[i]
    temp = merged[merged['State'] == state]

    axs.scatter(temp['MaxTemp'], temp['Assaults'])

    axs.set_title(state)
    axs.set_xlabel('Temp in Fahrenheit')
    axs.set_ylabel('Assaults')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()


#### Let's add some regression lines

import numpy as np

fig, axes = plt.subplots(2,5, figsize=(20,10))
axes = axes.flatten()

for i, state in enumerate(states):
    axs = axes[i]
    temp = merged[merged['State'] == state]

    x = temp['MaxTemp']
    y = temp['Assaults']

    axs.scatter(x,y)

    if len(x) > 1:
        m, b = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)
        axs.plot(x, m*x + b)


        axs.text(
            0.05, 0.90,
            f"y = {m:.2f}x +{b:.2f}",
            transform=axs.transAxes,
            fontsize=9
        )

        corr = x.corr(y)

        axs.text(
            0.05,0.80,
            f"r={corr:.2f}",
            transform=axs.transAxes,
            fontsize=9
        )

    axs.set_title(state)
    axs.set_xlabel('Temperature in Fahrenheit')
    axs.set_ylabel('Assaults')


plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()


## So, with correlation strong for some States and not the other States, it made me wonder if it was because of the temperature distribution in some States.
####
#### Essentially, if a State's weather is pretty stable year-round (e.g., California) the correlation between weather
#### won't be as strong or pronounced (if at all) because the weather is pretty much a moot factor. However, States that
#### have a percieved heavier swing in temperature (such as New York), the weather may have a bigger impact on aggravated assaults.

####
#### The next step was to see the distribution in temperature across the States.

states = weather_byDate['State'].unique()

fig, axes = plt.subplots(2,5,figsize=(18,8))
axes = axes.flatten()

for i, state in enumerate(states):
    axs = axes[i]
    temp = weather_byDate[weather_byDate['State'] == state]['MaxTemp']

    axs.boxplot(temp)
    axs.set_title(state)

    median = temp.median()
    axs.text(1.05, median, f"{median:.1f}", fontsize = 8)

    axs.set_xticks([])
    if i % 5 == 0:
        axs.set_ylabel('Temperature')
    if i >= 5:
        axs.set_xlabel('State')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

## Closing Statements
##
#### In closing, the scope of this lab was to review how temperature affected the number of aggravated assault arrests over
#### the 10 most populous States in the United States. This last figure, the boxplot, shows that the NOAA data is extremely compressed
#### and does not allow for an in-depth review of temperature impact on aggravated assaults. One way that this could be improved
#### is to pull the weather data from a different source that maybe provides the actual percieved temperature of the location
#### rather than a smoothed and controlled temperature line.
####
#### While the idea to consider a geographically diverse data set, it appears that the States are still to broad of a category
#### and considering the 10 most populous cities would have been a better consideration.
####
#### Due to time limitation for this lab, I will be concluding this review with some key takeaways:
#### <ul><li>Each State has a different average temperture that limits an aggregate correlation between all States without some data normalization</li> <li>New York, Pennsylvania, and North Carolina had the strongest correlation factors: this could be due to a greater seasonal variety in temperature</li><li>Florida, Georgia, and Michigan had the correlations closest to zero. This is a vindication of the large spread in their climate as noted in the scatterplot above</li><li>Texas has the stronges negative correlation (~.50) which [if we recall with our Arizona data] may seem to support the fact that there is a limit to human willing to tolerate the heat and maybe instead seek shelter instead</li>
